@node Introduction "Perch.  What a strange name."
Perch stands for @{b}Per@{ub}missions @{b}Ch@{ub}anger.  It basically
attempts to give FTPMount the ability to change permissions on remote files
(CHMOD command)


It is @{b}not@{ub} a patch - it's a completely separate program which uses
its own specialised FTP code, along with reading information from the
FTPMount directory structure.


@endnode

@node Installation
Simply put Perch where you want it and start it when you like!  It's
probably best to put it in WBStartUp.  It doesn't matter whether you start
it before or after FTPMount.

@endnode

@node usage "How to Perch"
Upon running Perch, it will add an entry to the "Tools" menu with the name
"CHMOD...".


Select a file from the FTPMount structure (make sure FTPMount is mounted!),
and select CHMOD... from the Tools menu.  A small window will pop up.  See
@{"the GUI" link gui}


Alternatively, you can control it with @{"ARexx" link arexx}

@endnode

@node gui "The GUI"
@{b}User@{ub}

Your username for the site.  This will be read from the FTPMount directory
tooltypes or from the user@host filename.  You can edit it here.  Please
note that changing to a different user than you log in as with FTPMount will
probably result in your home directory changing - Perch will not be able to
find the file if this happens!


@{b}Pass@{ub}

Your password for the username above.  This will be read from the FTPMount
PASSWORD tooltype, if possible.  Perch can @{b}not@{ub} decrypt
PASSWORDCRYPT.


@{b}Permissions Matrix@{ub}

The group of nine checkboxes shows who will have which permissions.  The
permission is shown to the far left of the checkbox, and the user type is
shown above the checkbox.


       Owner  Group  Other

Read

Write                  X

Exec


For example, if you check the box marked with an "X" above, you will give
ordinary users write permission for that file.  The most useful
combination is:


Read   Owner  Group  Other

Write  Owner

Exec   Owner  Group  Other


Which will set the appropriate permissions for a CGI script.  Please note
that your webspace has to support CGIs for this to work!


@{b}OK@{ub}

Sets the permissions of the file.


@{b}Cancel@{ub}

Closes the requester without setting permissions.


To quit Perch, either use Commodities Exchange (this may be removed in a
future release), or choose "CHMOD..." while no icons are selected and click
"Quit"

@endnode

@node arexx "ARexx Port"
Perch was originally designed to be used through Workbench.  However, I
received a question as to whether it could be integrated into a file
manager, and so the ARexx port was born.


Perch understands two commands.  Note that all spaces should be single
spaces only, and filenames @{b}must not@{ub} be enclosed in double-quotes.


@{b}CHMOD@{ub} filename

This is the equivalent to selecting "filename" from Workbench, and then
choosing CHMOD... from the menu.


@{b}QCHMOD@{ub} OGO filename

Where OGO is the permissions set to use:


       Owner  Group  Other

Read     1      1      1

Write    2      2      2

Exec     4      4      4


Add up the permissions you want in each column.  Note that you
@{b}must@{ub} have both USER and PASSWORD set in the FTPMount host
tooltypes, as QCHMOD does not prompt for missing information.



To add a feature to your file manager, consult the documentation.  The
action to perform should be something like:

Sys:Rexxc/rx "ADDRESS PERCH 'CHMOD %F'"

@endnode

@node history "What is this Perch, Histor?"
@{b}Version 1.1@{ub} (26.06.99)


* Added ARexx port


* Changed detection code for FTPMount to "FTP" from "FTPMount:".  This may
enable Perch to work with alternative FTP filesystems.


@{b}Version 1.0@{ub} (06.06.99)


First release

@endnode

